# Predicates:
Man(x) ::: x is a man.
Taller(x, y) ::: x is taller than y.
Block(x, y) ::: x can block y's shooting.
Shooting(y) ::: y is a shooting.
Class(x) ::: x is in Michael's class.
Person(x) ::: x is a person.
Jump(x) ::: x jumps when shooting.
GreatShooter(x) ::: x is a great shooter.
Shooter(x) ::: x is a shooter.
Michael(x) ::: x is Michael.
Peter(x) ::: x is Peter.
Windy(x) ::: x is Windy.

# Premises:
# --- General Definitions ---
Person(x)
Man(x) ::: Person(x)
Taller(x, y) ::: Person(x) ∧ Person(y)
Block(x, y) ::: Person(x) ∧ Person(y) # x can block y's shooting
Shooting(y) ::: Person(y) # y is performing a shooting
Class(x) ::: Person(x) # x is in Michael's class
Jump(x) ::: Person(x) # x jumps when shooting
GreatShooter(x) ::: Person(x)
Shooter(x) ::: Person(x)

# --- Specific Individuals ---
Michael(x)
Peter(x)
Windy(x)

# --- Axioms from the Scenario ---

# If a man is taller than another man, the taller one can block the other's shooting.
∀x ∀y (Man(x) ∧ Man(y) ∧ Taller(x, y) → Block(x, y))

# Michael is a man who is taller than everyone else in his class.
# This implies that anyone in Michael's class is NOT taller than Michael,
# and Michael is taller than anyone in his class.
# Assuming Michael is a man.
Man(michael)
∀x (Class(x) → Taller(michael, x))
# Add an edge case: Michael is not in his own class (or at least not taller than himself).
# We can enforce this by stating if x is in the class, then x is not Michael.
# Alternatively, if Michael is in his class, he isn't taller than himself.
# The first interpretation is more likely given "everyone else".
∀x (Class(x) → ¬Michael(x))

# If person x is taller than person y, and person y is taller than person z, than x is taller than z
∀x ∀y ∀z (Taller(x, y) ∧ Taller(y, z) → Taller(x, z))

# Peter is a man who is taller than Michael.
Man(peter)
Taller(peter, michael)

# Michael is a man.
Man(michael)

# Peter is a man.
Man(peter)

# Windy is a man.
Man(windy)

# Michael can block any shooting from a person as long as the person does not jump when shooting.
# The original states "person" here, implying Michael can block shooting from any person
# who doesn't jump, not just men.
∀x (Shooter(x) ∧ ¬Jump(x) → Block(michael, x)) # Block(michael, x) means Michael can block x's shooting

# Michael cannot block Windy's shooting.
# This is an exception to the previous rule.
¬Block(michael, windy)

# Every shooter who can jump when shooting is a great shooter.
∀x (Shooter(x) ∧ Jump(x) → GreatShooter(x))

# Conclusion:
GreatShooter(windy)
